<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06025062 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06025062 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  BOOK; PUBLICATION; COMPANY; MERGER; AGREEMENT; SALE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc., which struggled for nearly four years toremain independent despite a mountain of debt, said Thursday that its boardagreed to a $1.4 billion buyout by General Cinema Corp.;    The deal savesOrlando-based HBJ from almost certain bankruptcy and gives cash-rich GeneralCinema of Chestnut Hill, Mass., a good investment and its first taste of thepublishing and insurance businesses.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  GENERAL CINEMA TO BUY HBJDEBT-BURDENED PUBLISHER AGREES TO $1.4 BILLIONDEAL  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;All our employees have been working under this cloud of debt. Theimportant thing today is that we have lifted that cloud,&quot; said PeterJovanovich, HBJ's president, who will remain with the company after thebuyout.;    The buyout wipes clean HBJ's balance sheet, eliminating $1.8billion of debt that remained from a costly takeover defense against Britishpublisher Robert Maxwell.;    It also gives HBJ a chance to regain lost marketshare in its hallmark textbook publishing business, which suffered under themountain of debt.;    General Cinema owns 1,500 movie screens. The companyalso owns 40 percent of Neiman-Marcus, the ritzy department store chain. Ithas been interested in a publishing acquisition for about five years, saidPeter Farwell, a spokesman for General Cinema. It will pay for HBJ with astockpile of cash it accrued from the sale of a Pepsi-Cola bottling businessin 1989 and the sale of its investment in Cadbury Schweppes PLC last October.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Orlando Sentinel  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Orlando, Fla.  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910125  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1G  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUB